<p>I've already replied to your other thread.</p>
<blockquote>
<p>…is that possible, or are the documents I post (relatively) safe from plagiarism?</p>
</blockquote>
<p>Wikidot tracks edits. If you make a sandbox page, you'll be able to see every edit ever made on that page by any user who edited the text, through the &quot;History&quot; option. If you notice that a user other that yourself has been making edits, inform the staff, and we'll take care of it.</p>
<p>Again, if you see that anyone has taken your work and posted it to the site, if you can provide enough proof of the work being stolen, you shouldn't need to worry.</p>
<p>Besides, this is a wiki. No one's getting paid for this. Furthermore, if someone takes an idea written by someone else and is given critique on it, chances are if they're desperate enough to steal work, they might not understand how to fix it, and the entire thing is just a bad scenario for them.</p>

